Anonymous Thu 09 Sep 2021 18:50:30 No.41516098 Report
Quoted By: >>41516136 >>41516227 >>41516375 >>41516440 >>41516619 >>41520741
>>41515659
>>41515785
Foxes can vary wildly depending on the fox. Some absolutely love affection from everyone, others only allow affection from a few people, and others don’t allow it at all. In the case of the hands-off foxes, a lot are still bonded to a human, and get excited when they see their human, but still don’t allow touch. A trend across female foxes is when they’re around their heat, they get distant from others and tend to not allow touching, even if they do normally. And female foxes rarely get along with each other, at most, they’ll tolerate another’s presence.

Another thing you’ll want to look into is body language. When foxes see someone they love, they tend to lower themselves to the ground and/or roll onto their backs. Fox tails are similar to dogs in what emotion it shows, a rare instance of tail wagging I approve. I hate it when writers use tail wagging as a form of excitement on other animals, when it’s largely a dog/domesticated fox thing. Also, arctic foxes tend to point their tails up when excited.

And finally, and this is a fairly big one, foxes are not fighters. Whenever you see a fox in the wild, you’ll often see them in the distance, away from humans, unless they’re accustomed to them already. This is because a fox is naturally very skittish, and they don’t like confronting others. There may be a few squabbles over territory, or a red fox hunting an arctic fox, but that’s about it. And unless the fox has rabies, you’ll never see them attack a human. A fox’s main diet is small prey, berries, and carrion, they don’t see a living human as food, nor do they think they can take one down.

There are a few other small things, like how foxes like to sit on the heads of people they like to mark them, because foxes have a scent gland at the bottom of the base of their tail. Or how foxes practice food caching, but that’s about it for important stuff.

This has been my essay on foxes. Make of this what you will.

Anonymous Thu 09 Sep 2021 19:17:53 No.41516619 Report

>>41515785
Well first off, they're small. A wolf or a dog can match a human's mass but a fox doesn't come close, don't let the fluff fool you. I've only seen the size difference acknowledged in Look Don't Touch and that one where the anthros call humans 'Jagers'.
Then there's the smell. It's mostly the urine and male urine specifically, but foxes in general smell pretty distinct. Even if anthro versions wash up they're still going to be a bit muskier than most, to the point where even humans will comment on it if they get close.
Like most canids they've got strong senses of smell and hearing coupled with weak colour vision, but foxes also have good low-light vision, albeit not as good as cats.
Behaviour wise, they're crepuscular, meaning they prefer dawn and dusk over night or day; Anthro versions are likely to be most energetic at sunrise, they'll probably want to bed down at midday like a siesta, and then they'll have a second wind at sunset.
As >>41516098 says, they're timid and isolationist in the wild, but when it's the season to be social they're plenty affectionate, and monogamous to boot. It's worth reading the wikipedia article on their communication, there's a lot of good info on body language and the noises foxes make in those few paragraphs but it's not worth copypasting here. You said you're already watching rescue videos, and that's good, some of the things I've listed here come from random trivia in saveafox vids.
And finally I want to point you to a good example story to study. Out of the fics I've read, the best one at really emphasising the differences between its protags is End of Active Obligated Service. Anne's body language, tastes, and behaviour draw attention to her otherness constantly, coming together to make her seem not only like a blend of dog and human, but even a little bit alien, it's brilliantly executed.
